          "body": "The chapter closes with Solomon numbering 153,600 resident aliens and organizing them into the same three-tier structure named in verse 2: 70,000 carriers, 80,000 quarrymen, 3,600 supervisors (vv. 17-18). The Chronicler notes that Solomon uses David's prior census as his baseline — preparation is inherited, not invented from scratch. The deployment of alien labor on the Temple is theologically loaded for the post-exilic Chronicler. Isaiah 60:10 had promised: 'Foreigners will build up your walls'; 60:13 had named Lebanon's trees coming to 'beautify the place of My sanctuary.' What looks like administrative pragmatics — using available labor — is, in the Chronicler's canonical frame, anticipatory fulfillment. The nations are not merely instruments; they are participants in the restoration of proper worship in Jerusalem."
