          "title": "The chapter's canonical significance for the Chronicler's audience",
          "body": "The Chronicler writes for returnees from Babylon who are rebuilding both temple and community under Persian rule. Chapter 2 of 2 Chronicles is not antiquarian history for them — it is a template. Solomon organized labor (vv. 2, 17-18); Ezra and Nehemiah would need to do the same. Solomon secured international cooperation (vv. 3-16); the returnees received cooperation from Cyrus and Darius. Solomon grounded his building in the theological reality of God's greatness and incomprehensibility (vv. 5-6); the returnees needed to do the same rather than building a smaller temple out of diminished expectation. And Huram's doxology (vv. 11-12) reassured the post-exilic community that even in a world dominated by Gentile powers, those powers could recognize and honor the LORD of Israel. The chapter is simultaneously history, model, and promise."
